                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d377">
                <head>No. 373.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Drummond</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-08-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 27, 1881</date>. (Received August
                        30.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note to me of the 25th instant, respecting an incursion of Canadian Indians
                    in the neighborhood of Belknap, Montana Territory, and their raiding the United
                    States agency reservation, and in which you express your surprise and regret
                    that such should have taken place after the measure which had been taken by Her
                    Majesty’s Government to prevent the recurrence of these incursions.</p>
                <p>You also invite me to call the attention of Her Majesty’s Government to the facts
                    which you furnish me within your note.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to state that I shall carry out your wishes by the first mail,
                    and that I have this day transmitted a copy of your dispatch to the honorable
                    the deputy governor of Canada.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>VICTOR DRUMMOND.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
